## Is Artificial Intelligence Comparable to Human Intelligence. 


## Objective 

The objective of this essay was to explore whether Artificial Intelligence can be considered comparable to human intelligence. Through a structured debate, both sides presented arguments regarding what intelligence is and whether AI meets the requirements to be considered truly intelligent.

## Summary
The debate focused on two different perspectives. One side argued that intelligence should be defined by observable abilities such as learning, adapting, solving problems, and making decisions. From this point of view, modern AI systems demonstrate many characteristics associated with intelligence and should therefore be considered a legitimate form of intelligence.

The opposing side argued that human intelligence involves qualities that AI does not possess, such as consciousness, self-awareness, understanding, and emotional reasoning. Several philosophical concepts, including the Chinese Room argument, autonomy, embodiment, and causal reasoning, were used to support the idea that AI may simulate intelligence without actually understanding the information it processes.

Throughout the debate, both sides presented strong arguments and examples. The discussion ultimately showed that many disagreements about AI stem from different definitions of intelligence rather than disagreements about what AI systems are capable of doing.

## Final Thoughts 
Before working on this assignment, I mostly viewed intelligence as the ability to learn, solve problems, and make decisions. However, after researching both sides of the debate, I realized that intelligence is much more complicated than I initially thought. There are many characteristics that people associate with intelligence, including consciousness, understanding, autonomy, and self-awareness, and there is still no universally accepted definition.

One of the things I found most interesting was that many arguments about Artificial Intelligence are not really about the technology itself, but about how intelligence is defined. Depending on the definition being used, it is possible to reach very different conclusions about whether AI should be considered intelligent.

At the end of this debate, I realized that Artificial Intelligence is not only a technical field, but also one that raises important philosophical questions that may not have a single correct answer. This activity helped me think more critically about intelligence, human cognition, and the assumptions we make when comparing AI systems to human beings.